   Control   Core     Users  Lab     Low   Isolated
             Services         Clients Trust
```

---

## Architecture Model

- **Switch (Cisco SG300)** = Layer 2 segmentation only
- **Firewall (OPNsense)** = Layer 3 routing, NAT, DHCP, DNS, and inter-VLAN policy
- **Single trunk uplink (GE1)** carries all tagged VLAN traffic to the firewall

---

## VLAN 99 — MANAGEMENT
- **Subnet:** 192.168.99.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.99.1
- **Purpose:** Administrative control plane

**Devices:**
- Admin laptop (192.168.99.10)
- Cisco switch management (192.168.99.2)
- OPNsense management interface

**Access model:**
- Full administrative access to infrastructure
- Can access all VLANs when required
- No inbound access from other VLANs
- Note: OPNsense management UI is reachable only from physically assigned management ports (intentional hardening)

---

## VLAN 60 — SERVERS
- **Subnet:** 192.168.60.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.60.1
- **Purpose:** Core infrastructure and services

**Systems:**
- Domain Controller — Active Directory / DNS (192.168.60.10) — *operational*
- Splunk Server — SIEM (192.168.60.20) — *operational, running on dedicated VM*

**Access model:**
- Accessible from management VLAN
- Provides services (AD, Splunk) to lab VLAN
- No direct access from IoT or sandbox
- Limited exposure to home VLAN

> **Note:** QNAP NAS (formerly planned at 192.168.60.30) was removed and returned due to confirmed hardware failure. Storage role is currently unassigned pending a replacement solution.

---

## VLAN 30 — HOME NETWORK
- **Subnet:** 192.168.30.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.30.1
- **Purpose:** Controlled household network (transition from legacy)

**Devices:**
- TP-Link router (AP mode)
- Smart TV (temporary placement)
- Future migrated family devices

**Access model:**
- Internet access allowed
- No access to management VLAN
- No access to sandbox VLAN
- Blocked from servers and test VLANs (per current firewall rules)

---

## VLAN 20 — TEST / LAB CLIENT NETWORK
- **Subnet:** 192.168.20.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.20.1
- **Purpose:** Lab endpoint environment

**Devices:**
- Test PC (Dell Inspiron) — *domain-joined, active; Splunk Universal Forwarder installed and running*
- Windows Client VM
- Kali Linux VM (planned)
- Test printer
- Test phone (planned)

**Access model:**
- Internet access allowed (controlled)
- Access to server VLAN for AD and Splunk (log forwarding on 9997, domain services)
- No access to home VLAN
- No access to management VLAN

---

## VLAN 40 — IOT NETWORK
- **Subnet:** 192.168.40.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.40.1
- **Purpose:** Low-trust smart devices

**Devices:**
- Smart bulbs
- Air purifier
- Ring doorbell
- Wi-Fi extender
- IoT router/AP

**Access model:**
- Internet access only
- No access to internal VLANs
- Fully isolated from servers and management

---

## VLAN 50 — SANDBOX / MALWARE ZONE
- **Subnet:** 192.168.50.0/24
- **Gateway:** 192.168.50.1
- **Purpose:** High-risk testing environment

**Systems:**
- Sandbox VM (planned)
- Malware analysis systems (future)

**Access model:**
- No access to any internal VLANs
- No internet initially
- Future: controlled fake internet (INetSim)
- Fully isolated and monitored

---

## TRAFFIC FLOW MODEL

```text
    [Home VLAN] --------\
                         \
    [IoT VLAN] ---------- > OPNsense Firewall ---> Internet
                         /
    [Lab VLAN] ----------/

    [Servers VLAN] ---> provides services (AD, Splunk)

    [Management VLAN] ---> controls all infrastructure

    [Sandbox VLAN] ---> isolated (no trust, no access)
```

